abstract: IN his annual state-of-the-game message to the baseball brass assembled in Dallas, Bowie Kuhn struck a familiar note of doom. Unless "the most  buoyant urge to win" gave ground to "sanity in player salaries," said the commissioner, financial disaster lay ahead.
headline_main: Sports of The Times; The Prophet of Doom Is Heard Again
headline_print_headline: Sports of The Times; The Prophet of Doom Is Heard Again

abstract: CHOOSING life insurance can be a time-consuming and bewildering task, and now a group of state regulators--charged with  helping consumers make educated purchasing decisions--is suggesting that a model cost disclosure system be abandoned after only four years in existence.
headline_main: Your Money; Disclosing Cost Of Insurance

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 12--The men designated to be the two top economic officers in the Reagan administration met with senior Republican Senators today and were told that the 1981 Federal budget would exceed $662 billion, $30 billion more than the sum authorized by Congress last month.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 12--The Senate passed and sent to President Carter today a three-year extension of the revenue-sharing program for distributing Federal money to cities and states.

abstract: For every coach, says Fordham's Tom Penders, there is a label. "This guy is a recruiter, that guy turns a program around," said Penders, who brought the second tag to Rose Hill after his successes at Tufts and Columbia.

abstract: Al Davis, chief executive officer of the Oakland Raiders, has charged that Georgia Frontiere, the owner of the Los Angeles Rams, sold tickets to last season's Super Bowl game at above their face value, and that Pete Rozelle, the comissioner of the National Football League, may also have profited from such sales.
headline_main: Ram Owner, Rozelle Deny Bowl Scalping
headline_print_headline: Ram Owner, Rozelle Deny Bowl Scalping

abstract: HASTINGS-ON-HUDSON THE most striking thing, per  haps, was the fullness of the sound. The evening, after all, had been described as a hoote  nanny and a formal gathering of those who play folk music, and the connotation was of two or three guitars and just as many soft and silvery voices.
